# mint
[![Build Status](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://github.com/kvark/mint/workflows/check/badge.svg)](https://github.com/kvark/mint/actions) [![Docs](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://docs.rs/mint/badge.svg)](https://docs.rs/mint) [![Crates.io](https://img.shields.io/crates/v/mint.svg?maxAge=2592000)](https://crates.io/crates/mint)
**Math INteroperability Types**
![xkcd standard](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/standards.png)
This library provides standard mathematical types used in computer graphics. Its only purpose is to serve as a standard and interoperability language between various components of [rust-gamedev](http://arewegameyet.com/categories/math/) ecosystem that happen to expose math-related types on their API. There are no operations defined for the types other than for the means of conversion from/into external types. Serde support is available through the ``serde`` feature.

enriched_crate.readme_summary: The `mint` crate provides a collection of standard math types for computer graphics, such as vectors, points, matrices (row and column), quaternions, and Euler angles, designed to facilitate interoperability between libraries. It includes intrinsic and extrinsic rotation enums for 3D transformations and the `IntoMint` trait for seamless type conversion to mint equivalents. This crate serves as a lightweight, consistent interface for mathematical operations in graphics applications.
enriched_crate.factual_counterfactual:
### Pair 1: Math Interoperability  
✅ Factual: The `mint` crate provides standardized mathematical types, such as `Vector2`, `Vector3`, and `Quaternion`, to facilitate interoperability between different computer graphics libraries.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `mint` crate implements advanced numerical solvers for differential equations, making it suitable for scientific computing applications.  

---

### Pair 2: Matrix Representations  
✅ Factual: The `mint` crate supports both column-major and row-major matrix representations, such as `ColumnMatrix4` and `RowMatrix4`, to accommodate different library conventions.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `mint` crate only supports column-major matrices, making it incompatible with libraries that use row-major representations.  

---

### Pair 3: Euler Angles and Rotation  
✅ Factual: The `mint` crate includes structures like `EulerAngles` and enums like `ExtraZYX` to represent both intrinsic and extrinsic rotations in 3D space.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `mint` crate does not support Euler angle representations and relies exclusively on quaternions for all rotation-related operations.
